#: {{synonyms|en|Congolese giraffe|forest giraffe|zebra giraffe}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Harry [''i.e.'', Henry] H[amilton] Johnston|authorlink=Harry Johnston|title=The Okapi: The Newly-discovered Beast Living in Central Africa|magazine=[[w:McClure's|McClure’s Magazine]]|location=New York, N.Y.; London|publisher=[[w:S. S. McClure|S[amuel] S[idney] McClure Co.]]|month=September|year=1901|volume=XVII|issue=5|pages=498 and 499|pageurl=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.$b199974&view=1up&seq=516|oclc=3636477|passage=&#91;[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.$b199974&view=1up&seq=516 page 498, column 1]&#93; [I]n leading them [African Pygmies] back to the forests where they dwelt, I obtained much information from them on the subject of the horse-like animal which they called the "'''Okapi'''." {{...}} &#91;[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.$b199974&view=1up&seq=517 page 499, column 1]&#93; The coloration of the '''Okapi''' is quite extraordinary. {{...}} The hind quarters, hind and fore legs are either snowy white or pale cream color, touched here and there with orange. They are boldly marked, however, with purple-black stripes and splodges, which give that zebra-like appearance to the limbs of the '''Okapi''' that caused the first imperfect account of it to indicate the discovery of a new striped horse.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=C[harles] I[mmanuel] Forsyth Major|authorlink=Charles Immanuel Forsyth Major|title=On a Specimen of the Okapi Lately Received at Brussels|journal=[[w:Journal of Zoology|Proceedings of the Scientific Meetings of the Zoological Society of London]]|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for the}} [[w:Zoological Society of London|[Zoological] Society [of London]]]; Messrs. [[w:Longman|Longmans, Green, and Co.]],{{nb...|Paternoster Row.}}|date=18 November 1902|volume=I|page=344|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.26726/page/n828/mode/1up|issn=0370-2774|oclc=1131321218|passage=Personally I esteem it a more fascinating and a more important task to investigate the relations of the '''Okapi''' with the Giraffe on the one hand, and its fossil relatives on the other.}}
#* {{RQ:Saki Reginald|story=Reginald's Christmas Revel|page=98|passage=[O]ne day I quite modestly gave the dimensions of an '''okapi''' I had shot in the Lincolnshire fens. The Major turned a beautiful Tyrian scarlet (I remember thinking at the time that I should like my bathroom hung in that colour), and I think that at that moment he almost found it in his heart to dislike me.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=H[enry] H[amilton] Johnston|authorlink=Harry Johnston|title=Life Habits of the Okapi|journal=[[w:Nature (journal)|Nature: A Weekly Illustrated Journal of Science]]|location=London|publisher=[[w:Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan and Co.]]; New York, N.Y.: [[w:Macmillan Inc.|The Macmillan Company]]|date=26 August 1915|volume=95|issue=2391|page=714|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/paper-doi-10_1038_095713a0/page/n1/mode/1up|column=1|oclc=64051812|passage=Dr. [[w:Cuthbert Christy|[Cuthbert] Christy]] adds his testimony to that of his predecessors in the same quest as to the "invisibility" of the '''okapi''', whose markings and coloration—''pace'' Colonel {{w|Theodore Roosevelt}}—so break up the surface of its large body and long legs as to cause it to fuse with the dark-brown, russet, while and yellow-white of the twigs and stems and leaf-stalks amongst which it moves. He also points out that the hoofs of the '''okapi''' are so closely pressed together that the footprint is almost like that of the single-toed donkey.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=T[homas] Alexander Barns|authorlink=Thomas Alexander Barns|chapter=To the Game-haunted Solitudes of Ruchuru and Ruindi Plains|title=The Wonderland of the Eastern Congo: The Region of the Snow-crowned Volcanoes, the Pygmies, the Giant Gorilla and the Okapi|location=London; New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:G. P. Putnam's Sons|G[eorge] P[almer] Putnam’s Sons]]|month=May|year=1922|page=99|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/wonderlandofeas00barn/page/99/mode/1up|oclc=977951802|passage=I also took out a licence to shoot small game, costing fifty francs, which can be obtained on the spot, and under which I was able to shoot all kinds of game, excepting elephants, chimpanzis, gorillas and '''okapis'''.}}

